   Technology Brief -- Epitope Inc.:
   FDA Clears Clinical Trials
   For Company's AIDS Test
</HL>
<DATE>
08/08/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4
</SO>
<CO>
   EPT
</CO>
<IN>
MEDICAL AND BIOTECHNOLOGY (MTC)
</IN>
<GV>
FOOD AND DRUG ADMINISTRATION (FDA)
</GV>
<LP>
   Epitope Inc. said the Food and Drug Administration
approved its application to begin human clinical trials on a
saliva-based AIDS diagnostic test.
   Epitope said preclinical trials show the test to be as
accurate as blood tests taken to detect the AIDS virus. The
clinical trials, expected to last for nine months, will be
conducted in hospitals, laboratories, medical centers and
dental schools in San Francisco; Tampa, Fla.; Portland, Ore.;
New York; and Chicago.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The Beaverton, Ore., biotechnology concern said its system
uses a saliva collection kit. The results are placed in a
sealed tube and sent to company labs for testing.
