<HL>
   Yields on CDs Slipped
   During Latest Week
</HL>
<DATE>
08/08/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C17
</SO>
<IN>
CDS, INTEREST RATES, COMMERCIAL PAPER (FIN)
BANKS (BNK)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Yields on certificates of deposit at major
banks and brokerage firms fell slightly in the week ended
Tuesday.
   The average yield on six-month small-denomination CDs sold
directly by banks slipped to 7.42% from 7.53%, according to
an 18-bank national survey by Banxquote Money Markets, a New
York information service. The average yield for five-year
consumer CDs fell to 7.87% from 8.01%.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Average yields on small-denomination CDs sold by leading
broker dealers were also down. The exception was the average
yield on five-year broker-sold CDs, which edged up to 8.28%
from 8.27%. The average yield on a one-year CD fell to 7.72%
from 7.80%, while the average for two-year CDs eased to 8.04%
from 8.10%, according to Banxquote.
   Average yields for "jumbo" CDs, which typically require
deposits of $90,000 or more, declined. The average yield on
one-year jumbo CDs eased to 7.60% from 7.68%, while the
average for five-year maturities slipped to 8.12% from 8.16%.
</TEXT>
