<HL>
   Letters to the Editor:
   Education System
   Ruined by `Fixing'
</HL>
<DATE>
08/08/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A11
</SO>
<LP>
   Christopher de Vinck has hit the nail right on the head in
asserting that real books should be at the core of education
reform (editorial page, July 9). Books do so much more than
just tell a story: They improve vocabulary, grammar skills
and writing proficiency simply by providing a good example.
Plus, books stimulate the imagination and provoke thought,
and critical thinking is the essence of a good education.
Real books, then, must be the foundation of learning.
   The question I have, then, is why did we get away from
using real books in the first place? Literature worked just
fine for hundreds of years. It seems the "blue-ribbon
conferences" and the so-called experts that set out to
"improve" education have done just the opposite. They forgot
a fundamental rule of life: If it ain't broke, don't fix it.
The problem was not in the curriculum -- the problem was, and
still is, in the administration of education. A tenure system
that prevents underperforming teachers from being fired, the
practice of promoting students who fail to meet even basic
scholastic requirements, and the continued use of the
nine-month school year, an anachronism from the Farm Age --
these are the problems that need to be addressed. Solve them,
and education will improve dramatically.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   David L. Corts Jr.
   Samford University '90
   Birmingham, Ala.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900808-0068
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900808-0068.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   U.S. Postal Service Deficit
   To Be Less Than Expected
</HL>
<DATE>
08/08/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A2
</SO>
<GV>
POSTAL SERVICE (POS)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The Postal Service said it's making progress
in boosting productivity and narrowing losses, but not enough
to affect its plans for a new round of rate increases.
   The estimated postal deficit for the fiscal year ending
Sept. 30 will be less than $1 billion, compared with the $1.6
billion loss originally projected, Postmaster General Anthony
Frank told his board of governors and a news conference. He
credited the narrowing to productivity gains, which have been
escalating over the past 12 months, reaching 3.4% in the
quarter ended June 30.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The benefits of a major postal automation program and a
recently imposed ceiling on employment levels are responsible
for improving productivity, Mr. Frank said. The Postal
Service has been installing automatic equipment that reads
envelopes and sorts them according to nine-digit address
codes. Hiring curbs also have helped reduce its work force by
23,000, to 764,000, since June 1989, officials said.
   But Mr. Frank said the improvement isn't sufficient to
alter the plan to boost rates by an average of 19%, including
an increase of five cents to 30 cents for first-class
service. The rise would occur early in 1991, after
consideration by the Postal Rate Commission.
   In defending the rate increase's size, Mr. Frank noted the
uncertainty over how well the agency can do in holding down
labor costs in talks with unions, which begin late this
month, and the White House budget office's efforts to require
the service to contribute $1.3 billion to U.S. deficit
reduction.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900808-0067
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900808-0067.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Letters to the Editor:
   Forget the Dream of Military Primacy
</HL>
<DATE>
08/08/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A11
</SO>
<CO>
   FREST
</CO>
<IN>
INTERNATIONAL ECONOMIC NEWS AND STATISTICS (IEN)
AEROSPACE (ARO)
</IN>
<LP>
   Martin Feldstein's article "Trade Economic Aid for Soviet
Arms Cuts" (editorial page, June 28) described how the U.S.
could reach "clear military superiority" over the Soviet
Union. From his point of view, it would be foolish not to
spend "a few tens of billions of dollars" to obtain a major
reduction in Soviet military capacity in exchange for massive
economic aid.
   In other words, he suggests using recent Soviet economic
difficulties to fulfill an old dream in the West -- military
superiority over the Soviet Union.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Even though he mentions the necessity of some U.S.
military reductions, the U.S. superiority thus obtained
supposedly would ensure peace for the rest of the world. Can
you imagine what the American reaction would be if some
people in the Soviet Union aspired to the role of "world
peacekeepers" in such a manner?
   Mr. Feldstein is wrong in thinking my country could ever
sell its security for consumer goods and know-how. Recently,
the Communist Party Congress in Moscow adopted a resolution
on national defense policy saying in particular that a
military threat to the Soviet Union persists as long as there
are no guarantees of the irreversibility of positive changes
in the military and political situation. Under these
conditions the Party Congress considers it a major task to
strengthen and maintain the Soviet Union's defense capacity
at a reasonably sufficient level.
   As one can see from the example of the postwar period, the
desire to have military superiority has fed the arms race and
increased international tension and the threat of war. The
belief in my country is that the existing rough parity
between the Soviet Union and the U.S., and between the Warsaw
Treaty Organization and NATO, is the decisive factor
preventing wars. This parity should be maintained, but at
steadily decreasing levels.
   The Soviet Union is already applying this principle. From
1989 to the end of this year the Soviet armed forces will be
unilaterally reduced by 500,000 men and officers, 10,000
tanks, 8,500 artillery systems and 820 combat aircraft. In
1989 it unilaterally reduced its armed forces by 265,000 men
and officers, withdrew 27,400 servicemen from the Northern,
Western, Central and Southern groups of forces in Europe and
22,900 from Mongolia. The number of Soviet weapons in Europe
went down by 9,320 tanks, 5,050 artillery systems and 835
warplanes.
   More than 59,000 servicemen, 1,370 tanks, more than 1,040
artillery systems and 173 combat aircraft have been withdrawn
from Czechoslovakia, Hungary, Poland and Mongolia this year.
   The Soviet navy has scrapped 12 submarines and 28 surface
ships, and moth-balled three submarines and 11 surface ships.
Besides, 500 tactical nuclear charges have been withdrawn
from Warsaw Treaty countries. The Soviet Union is prepared to
pull all its nuclear weapons out from allied countries, if
the U.S. acts likewise.
   The restructuring of the Soviet armed forces is proceeding
under the sign of defense. But realization of defense
sufficiency is possible only on the basis of reciprocity.
   Reciprocity is the only way to curb the arms race and
disarm. This is the best way we have of achieving, using Mr.
Feldstein's words, "greater military security" and "greater
global stability." And it is also the best way for the U.S.
to reduce safely its own military spending.
   Alexander Malyshkin
   Senior Information Officer
   Soviet Embassy
   Washington
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900808-0066
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900808-0066.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Corporate Giving to Rise
   5% in 1990, Survey Says
</HL>
<DATE>
08/08/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A2
</SO>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Corporate giving to education and charitable
causes rose a meager 3% in 1989, and is likely to grow only
5% this year, according to a survey by the Council for Aid to
Education.
   After more than a decade of annual increases averaging
15%, corporate contributions began to drop off in 1988, the
council said. A spokeswoman attributed the slowing rate to
changing tax laws, mixed corporate profits and uncertainty
over the economy.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Increases in donations to education also have slowed in
recent years, the survey found. Contributions to education
rose 4% in 1989 and 6% in 1988, after 12 years of
double-digit jumps.
   In addition to curbing their largess, the study found
companies are redirecting their gifts. The share of dollars
devoted specifically to pre-college education jumped 10.5% in
1989, after years of much smaller increases.
   Total corporate giving to all causes in 1989 rose to an
estimated $6.5 billion, or about 2.1% of pretax corporate
profits. Giving to education rose to $2.8 billion, or 0.9% of
corporate profits, the council estimated. The growth in
corporate giving in 1988 was only 2%, the council now
estimates, down from an earlier estimate of 3.2%.
   Data for the survey were provided by 333 companies, which
account for 25% of corporate giving.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900808-0065
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900808-0065.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Who's News:
   Ruff Said He Was
   Fired as President
   Of FundAmerica
   ---
   Newsletter Publisher Says
   Action Was Due to His
   Remarks About Founder
   ----
   By Rhonda L. Rundle
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
08/08/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B9
</SO>
<CO>
   WNEWS
</CO>
<IN>
DIVERSIFIED FINANCIAL SERVICES, FANNIE MAE, FREDDIE MAC (FIS)
</IN>
<LP>
   Howard Ruff, a financial newsletter publisher who was
named president of FundAmerica Inc. last week, said he was
fired by the company's Canadian owners because of his
disclosure of $17 million in withdrawals by the company
founder.
   FundAmerica is an Irvine, Calif.-based discount buying
club under investigation by Florida authorities. Mr. Ruff
assumed the top post there after founder Robert T. Edwards
resigned in the wake of his arrest last month on charges of
organized fraud and conducting an illegal lottery.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Texas real-estate developer Mitchell Blumberg is
succeeding Mr. Ruff as president and chief executive officer.
"We thought our chances of survival would be better with Mr.
Blumberg," a FundAmerica spokesman said. Mr. Blumberg didn't
return phone calls for comment.
   FundAmerica remains "firmly in the hands of Bob Edwards'
friends and business associates," Mr. Ruff said in a
statement. Mr. Blumberg and Mr. Edwards have been real-estate
associates in Texas, Mr. Ruff has said.
   A Newport Beach, Calif., attorney, whose firm represents
FundAmerica, said in a San Francisco court Monday that
FundAmerica had told him it "was a 99% probability" that the
company would file for bankruptcy-law protection. Yesterday,
the attorney said FundAmerica had retained a separate law
firm that specializes in bankruptcy matters.
   The FundAmerica spokesman said he wasn't aware of any such
plans.
   FundAmerica is owned by FundAmerica Holdings Ltd., a
closely held British Columbia corporation. Mr. Edwards is a
major shareholder and director. He and other shareholders
have placed all of their shares in a trust controlled by
Peter Bradshaw, a consultant to the U.S. company. Neither Mr.
Bradshaw nor Mr. Edwards, free on $1 million bail, could be
reached.
   Several days after he became chief executive, Mr. Ruff
announced that Mr. Edwards had personally made $17 million in
withdrawals from FundAmerica this year, including about $11
million in wire transfers to various entities in Amsterdam
and Hong Kong.
   Florida authorities have filed a cease-and-desist order
against FundAmerica, charging that the club is an elaborate
pyramid scheme. The fund sells $100 annual memberships
entitling members to rebates on vacations, credit-card
purchases, long-distance telephone calls and purchases of
consumer goods.
   Fund America Investor Corp., a Denver-based issuer of
bonds and other securities, said it isn't affiliated with
FundAmerica.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900808-0064
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900808-0064.
