</DOCID>
<HL>
   The Mideast Conflict:
   CBS News Debated Impact
   Of Report on U.S. Security
</HL>
<DATE>
08/08/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A6
</SO>
<CO>
   CBS MDEST CCB GE TBSA
</CO>
<IN>
MEDIA, PUBLISHING, BROADCASTING, ELECTRONIC PUBLISHING (MED)
</IN>
<GV>
DEFENSE DEPARTMENT (DEF)
</GV>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- When CBS News reported exclusively the
deployment of U.S. troops to Saudi Arabia, it followed a
prolonged discussion within the network of whether the report
would affect national security.
   "On balance, we felt this was such an important story that
the American public deserved to know," said Joseph Peyronnin,
vice president and assistant to the president at CBS News, a
division of CBS Inc.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   CBS News broke the story at 3:33 p.m. with a report from
its Defense Department correspondent David Martin. Mr. Martin
said, "Frankly, we're reporting this after considerable
debate about whether to report in advance on a troop
movement."
   But once CBS News broke the news, it was quickly followed
by ABC News, a unit of Capital Cities/ABC Inc. NBC News -- a
division of General Electric Co.'s National Broadcasting Co.
unit -- went on the air with its story at 4:06. A spokeswoman
said NBC was the first network to report that U.S. troops
were already in Saudi Arabia.
   A spokeswoman for Cable News Network in Atlanta said, "We
had been reporting troop movements out of Fort Bragg {N.C.},
Fort Stewart {Ga.} and Langley Air Force Base {Va.} all
morning." She said CNN reported President Bush's decision to
send troops to Saudi Arabia at 3:44 p.m., citing the CBS
report.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900808-0037
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900808-0037.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Business Brief -- Sbarro Inc.:
   Fast Food Chain Reports
   Net Rose 43% for Period
</HL>
<DATE>
08/08/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   SBA
</CO>
<IN>
EARNINGS (ERN)
</IN>
<LP>
   Sbarro Inc., the Commack, N.Y., Italian fast food
restaurant chain, reported a 43% rise in net income for the
12 weeks ended July 15.
   Net income for the period was $3.5 million, or 26 cents a
share, up from $2.4 million, or 18 cents a share, in the
year-earlier period. Sales rose 32% to $40.3 million from
$30.6 million.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Sbarro said that for the twenty-eight weeks, net income
rose 42% to $7.2 million, or 54 cents a share, from $5.1
million, or 38 cents a share. Sales rose 32% to $88.8 million
from $67.4 million.
   Of the 419 restaurants operating under the Sbarro name
during the recent period, 100 were franchised. A year ago
there were 343 units in operation, and 86 were franchised.
   Sbarro shares closed yesterday at $28.375, up $1.25 in
composite trading on the American Stock Exchange.
</TEXT>
