<HL>
   Marketing &amp; Media:
   U.S. Files Suit to Block
   Procter &amp; Gamble Plan
</HL>
<DATE>
08/08/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   PG RPR RP.C
</CO>
<IN>
HOUSEHOLD AND PERSONAL-CARE PRODUCTS (HHP)
</IN>
<GV>
JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Justice Department, as expected,
filed suit to block a plan by Procter &amp; Gamble Co., the maker
of Pepto-Bismol, to acquire the exclusive sales rights for
Maalox, another stomach remedy.
   The Justice Department sought a court injunction under the
Clayton AntiTrust Act to prevent Procter &amp; Gamble from
acquiring the exclusive rights to market and distribute
Maalox.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Court papers filed in federal court in Philadelphia
charged that the proposed agreement between Cincinnati-based
Procter &amp; Gamble and Rhone-Poulenc Rorer Inc., which makes
Maalox, would lessen competition in the market of
over-the-counter stomach remedies.
   Procter &amp; Gamble, based in Cincinnati, sold $125 million
of Pepto-Bismol last year, or 14% of the domestic retail
market. Domestic sales of Maalox totaled $111 million last
year, or 12% of the market.
   Under the proposal, Procter &amp; Gamble would acquire the
exclusive rights to market and sell Maalox and an option to
purchase the manufacturing assets from Rhone-Poulenc Rorer,
which is based in Fort Washington, Pa. The deal would make
Procter &amp; Gamble the largest seller of stomach remedies in
the U.S. market, according to the complaint.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
