   What's News --
   Business and Finance
</HL>
<DATE>
08/08/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1
</SO>
<LP>
   SAUDI ARABIA AGREED to boost its oil output to help make
up for the loss of supplies from Iraq and occupied Kuwait,
U.S. officials said. The Saudis haven't yet pledged to a
specific figure, but the Bush administration was seeking a
commitment to increase production by about two million
barrels a day. Meanwhile, global sanctions against Iraq began
to cut into its petroleum exports.
                                                                                                       

</LP>
<TEXT>
   U.S. oil drillers are ill prepared to boost output in
response to a world petroleum shortage because of a lack of
equipment and experienced staff.
   ---
   Bond prices fell sharply and stocks swung wildly as
oil-related news shook the financial markets during the day.
Long-term Treasury bonds dropped half a point. The Dow Jones
industrials fell 5.70 points, to 2710.64, their sixth
consecutive loss. Broader stock indexes rose slightly. Signs
of escalating tension buoyed the dollar. st
   ---
   A federal budget accord is likely to come sooner because
of the Mideast crisis and its likely economic effects. But
the deficit-cutting goal for the first year will probably be
lowered.
   ---
   Tokyo stock prices tumbled Tuesday on concerns about the
Mideast. The Nikkei fell 946.46 points, or 3.3%. In morning
trading Wednesday, the index recovered 359.08 points.
   ---
   American Airlines is expected to disclose plans to raise
ticket prices by 10%. The move could supply the necessary
momentum to sustain industrywide fuel-related fare increases.
   ---
   Guarantees on Iraqi debt could cost the governments of the
West, Japan and the Soviet Union tens of billions of dollars.
Some international banks, meanwhile, could lose billions of
dollars lent to Kuwait's banks.
   ---
   Domestic coal producers could enjoy a comeback by
expanding output at existing mines if the oil crisis pushes
up coal demand and prices.
   ---
   Emerson Electric plans to spin off to shareholders its
defense units because they aren't profitable enough, despite
$600 million in annual sales. The move is another sign of
hard times ahead for military contractors.
   ---
   The growth in consumer credit slowed to a 0.8% annual rate
in June from 6.1% in May, indicating wariness among
consumers. Auto-purchase debt declined, while bank-card and
retail-store credit rose.
   ---
   Pfizer plans to set up a registry of more than 55,000
patients who received a potentially defective heart valve
sold by Pfizer's Shiley unit. The registry would be one of
the first ever developed for a medical device.
   ---
   The Manville personal-injury trust would be combined with
other firms' funds and turned into a national facility for
settling all asbestos cases, under a proposal by a federal
judge.
   ---
   A former Texas S&amp;L owner and three ex-officers were
indicted on charges stemming from the alleged misapplication
of $121.1 million.
   ---
   Quaker Oats expects to post lower profit for the current
quarter. The food firm cited rising marketing costs.
   ---
   Bank of New York withdrew as a primary dealer of U.S.
government securities, citing declining profits.
   ---
   Markets --
   Stocks: Volume 231,580,000 shares. Dow Jones industrials
2710.64, off 5.70; transportation 964.78, off 15.51;
utilities 204.41, off 0.51.
   Bonds: Shearson Lehman Hutton Treasury index 3361.94, off
8.73.
   Commodities: Dow Jones futures index 132.54, up 0.08; spot
index 132.32, up 0.16.
   Dollar: 150.95 yen, up 0.63; 1.5875 marks, up 0.0110.
