<HL>
   Oil Firms Fret as Tempers Boil, Prices Jump
   ---
   PR Challenge
   Being Fumbled,
   Experts Claim
   ----
   By Amanda Bennett
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
08/08/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B1
</SO>
<CO>
   MDEST
</CO>
<IN>
PETROLEUM (PET)
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
OIL, INTEGRATED MAJORS (OIL)
ADVERTISING, MARKETING, PUBLIC RELATIONS (ADV)
</IN>
<LP>
   Turmoil in the Mideast has handed American oil companies a
big public relations challenge: How to explain why prices at
the pump jumped so fast.
   But so far, industry experts and crisis management
consultants say, the oil companies are fumbling, shouldering
the brunt of Americans' anger even though the situation may
be beyond their control.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   "The oil industry must enjoy wearing the black hat," says
Paul Fullmer, president of the Chicago-based public-relations
firm Selz, Seabolt &amp; Associates. "They have again dropped the
ball."
   But others say that, given the circumstances, the oil
companies are doing the best they can. "Given the
uncertainties in the Middle East, it's probably inappropriate
for them to do much more than they are doing," says Robert
Dilenschneider, chief executive of Hill &amp; Knowlton, a public
relations firm that advises major oil companies. "It's like
driving on a mountain in a heavy storm. You're not sure
what's around the next bend."
   Still, any mistakes could prove costly in the long run.
U.S. oil companies are already reeling from such public
relations disasters as the grounding of the Exxon Valdez. In
the early 1970s, oil shortages and price increases after the
Arab oil embargo helped lead to the loss of some industry tax
credits, the passage of a windfall profits tax and an
antitrust complaint against the eight biggest oil companies.
   This time, industry officials fear that the public outcry
could set back industry efforts to regain drilling rights in
environmentally sensitive areas -- at a time when the
industry needs them the most.
   The oil companies say they are doing all they can to
explain why price increases are necessary. "Our policy is to
be prompt, straightforward, sincere and honest with all
inquiries," Shell Oil Co. said in a written response to
questions yesterday. "We recognize we are dealing with an
extremely volatile and consumer-sensitive area."
   Douglas Elmets, director of media relations for Atlantic
Richfield Co., says that between the time of the invasion and
yesterday afternoon, he was interviewed 92 times, while the
president of the company's marketing arm was involved in six
interviews with TV stations, one with radio and three with
major newspapers.
   But even those who have tried to get their positions out
to the public say the industry could do better. Dale Basye,
manager of corporate communications at Chevron Corp., says
the company had up to 10 people at once answering inquiries,
and made senior economists available for a televised rebuttal
of an industry pricing critic's charges.
   Still, he says, the company hasn't yet decided whether to
involve senior corporate officers: "It's something we've been
looking at," he says. "Unfortunately, it's been reactive up
to this point. Now we are looking at ways to take the
initiative."
   And privately, some industry spokespeople bemoan the
industry's passivity. "You always say we wish we had {done
more}," says one. "I'm not the decision maker." Another
complains that competitors were "unwilling or reluctant" to
address the topic directly, while yet another berates
industry officials for "burying their heads in the sand."
   Since the industry takes the position that immediate price
increases are necessary and unavoidable, public relations and
crisis experts say, the industry should have moved much more
quickly and actively to explain that. In particular, they
say, a crisis in which oil supplies were interrupted and
prices rose quickly was predictable, so the oil companies
should have prepared their dealer network to deal with it.
   "They should have had illustrations available on how the
whole domino effect takes place, and posters and handouts
available for dealers," says Mr. Fullmer of Selz Seabolt. "If
they were done ahead of time, they could have been printed
within a day or two."
   Mary Woodell, a crisis management director at consultants
Arthur D. Little Inc., agrees. "It's the dealer or retailer
who takes the heat. I would advise them to give dealers as
much advance notice as possible, a short statement of
purpose, of why we are doing this, so that they have
something to say to the people who go to the gas tank."
Otherwise, she says, "the retailer can be left flat-footed
and bearing the brunt of the blame."
   Mobil Corp. says such materials for dealers are "in the
pipeline."
   Others suggest that oil companies should have tried harder
to align themselves with the American public against a
common, outside, enemy. Otherwise, says Ian Mitroff, director
of the Center for Crisis Management at the University of
Southern California's business school, the blame falls on the
oil companies by default: "When you can't do much about an
external threat, you have to project and put that threat
somewhere. That's Freud 101. The anger has to go somewhere,
especially when you feel impotent."
   Herbert Schmertz, a former senior public affairs official
with Mobil Corp., now heads a private consulting company
bearing his name. He believes that oil companies should have
quickly seized the initiative to try to affect U.S. energy
policy: "There is a need to explain to the American public
{that} by misguided governmental policies we have put
ourselves in a position where we are dependent both
politically and economically on imported oil. They should be
making that case to the American public," he says, adding, "I
don't see any sign of it."
   Mr. Schmertz, long an advocate of lobbying aggressively
directly to the public, recommends a combination of paid
advertising and sending oil company executives out to speak.
   (See related story: "Debates Increase on Capitol Hill and
at Pumps" -- WSJ Aug. 8, 1990)
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900808-0002
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900808-0002.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Commodities:
   Copper Prices Post Modest Gains, but Early Surge
   Falters on Mixed Outlook for World Economies
   ----
   By John Valentine
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
08/08/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C12
</SO>
<IN>
COMMODITY NEWS, FARM PRODUCTS (CMD)
COMMODITY MARKETS FOR METALS (MIN)
PRECIOUS METALS, STONES, GOLD, SILVER (PCS)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Copper futures prices strongly extended
Monday's resurgence in early trading, rising to new
life-of-contract highs. But they couldn't sustain the
advances, and futures finished with only modest gains.
   The September contract ended only 0.95 cent a pound higher
at $1.2730 after trading as high as $1.3030.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Analysts said that, with the slowing U.S. economy and the
consequent softer demand for copper, traders were focusing on
the continuing strong economies of Japan and West Germany.
   The Mideast crisis in recent days has stirred concern that
the boom in oil prices might hurt world-wide economies,
resulting in a general slowdown in copper consumption.
Presumably Japan, a major copper importer, would be among
those most affected.
   However, said William O'Neill, senior commodity strategist
for Merrill Lynch, New York, "The focus in the market is on
the short term, rather than on the long view with its
economic considerations."
   Japan hasn't eased up on its aggressive purchases of
copper in London, Mr. O'Neill said, and it has "been the
engine for the price firmness."
   Fred Demler, metal economist at PaineWebber, New York,
said: "Copper imports into Japan are up 35% this year vs. a
year ago and are expected to continue to rise. Brass mills
there are looking for a large increase in copper consumption
later this year."
   Mr. Demler said that although sharp increases in world oil
prices triggered worldwide recessions in 1974 and 1980, "I
think traders are focusing on what is happening now."
   The pending unification of West and East Germany has
stimulated housing construction and brass-mill consumption of
copper there, he said.
   World-wide, Mr. Demler said, both supply and demand are
subject to negative factors. On the one hand, global
inventories of refined copper currently are up 85,000 tons
since the end of the first quarter at 655,000 tons, or about
four weeks' consumption.
   On the other hand, he said, world mining production of
copper in the first five months of this year was 2% below
that of the year-earlier period. The drop in mine production
will probably lead to tightness in refined production in the
third quarter and possibly in the fourth, he said.
   John Rogers, vice president of Regan MacKenzie Inc., a
Seattle brokerage firm, said: "People are forgetting that the
U.S. is no longer the world's major copper consumer.
Therefore, a slowdown in the U.S. economy doesn't have a
significant impact on the overall world copper picture."
   As a result, he said, he sees no sign of a collapse in
copper prices. "Considering that production costs of copper
range between 85 cents and 90 cents a pound, $1 a pound for
copper can be justified in the foreseeable future," Mr.
Rogers said.
   "There are those who look at the long term and say that
copper prices can go back to 65 cents a pound," he said.
"That's not likely to happen, barring a major recession or a
depression."
   One dealer, who asked to remain anonymous, said: "Most
people are thoroughly confused as to where the copper market
is going. You can flip a coin at this point, and one side is
as good as the other."
   Over the long term, he said, if inflation strikes because
of the oil crisis, "the higher cost of doing business is bad
for the economy and bad for copper." But on the other hand,
he said, conflict can be good for copper, which is used in
making armaments.
   In other commodity markets yesterday:
                                                                                                       

   PRECIOUS METALS: Futures prices were lower. December
delivery gold recovered from early declines to end 10 cents
an ounce lower at $393.70. September silver was off 3.2 cents
an ounce at $4.8880. October platinum ended with a loss of
$8.30 an ounce at $482.10 but at one point traded as low as
$477.50. There was less of a crisis atmosphere early in the
day, and gold prices slumped, analysts said. However, Mideast
tensions mounted later, and gold recovered almost all its
losses. Cash market demand for gold bullion was "spotty," an
analyst said. The weakness in platinum was attributed to a
reduced likelihood of violence in South Africa after news
that the African National Congress had suspended its
guerrilla campaign, the analyst said.
                                                                                                       

   GRAINS AND SOYBEANS: Prices of corn, wheat and soybean
futures settled mixed at the Chicago Board of Trade. Traders
are caught between two schools of thought. Some are
speculating that Soviet purchases of U.S. crops might
accelerate as the rise in oil prices helps the Soviet Union
generate more revenue from its oil fields. At the same time,
prices are being depressed by the approach of what will
probably be relatively large harvests of corn and soybeans.
Although an unusually wet spring and summer in the Midwest
slowed the maturity of the crops, they are generally in good
condition. Corn for September delivery ended at $2.54 a
bushel, down a quarter of a cent, while September soybeans
rose half a cent to $6.0025 a bushel.
                                                                                                       

   SUGAR: Futures prices rose slightly. The October contract
ended with a gain of 0.08 cent a pound at 10.50 cents. Demand
developed after a report that China had bought 50,000 to
80,000 tons of raw sugar. "This indicates there is demand for
sugar at these low prices," an analyst said. Another
price-supporting development, the analyst said, was Brazil's
announcement late Monday that it would suspend imports of
Iraqi oil. This led to speculation that Brazil might use more
sugar to make ethanol, an alternative fuel, and consequently
would have less sugar to export, according to the analyst.
Another factor was Hurricane Diana, which was approaching the
Mexican coast near sugar-growing areas, the analyst said,
creating concern about possible crop damage.
